{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658268"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20723"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20723"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96811"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13599"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79426"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11727"},{"type":"tags","id":"11728"},{"type":"tags","id":"12608"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32716"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EYou are working in the Emergency Department when asked to collect a group and screen sample for a 67-year-old woman admitted with a neck of femur fracture. You notice the specimen label shows \u0027Margaret Wilson, DOB 15/03/1956, MRN 123456\u0027, while the pathology request form shows \u0027Margaret Wilton, DOB 15/03/1956, MRN 123456\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proceed with collection as the difference is minor","Delay collection until the discrepancy is resolved","Collect the specimen but mark it as potentially mislabelled","Ask the patient to confirm her identity verbally and proceed","Use only the medical record number for identification"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario addresses a critical patient safety issue related to patient identification in pathology specimen collection. When there is a discrepancy between the patient\u0027s identification band and the pathology request form, even a seemingly minor one like a spelling difference in the surname, proper protocol must be followed to prevent potential patient harm from specimen misidentification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelay collection until the discrepancy is resolved\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate action. According to hospital protocols and safety standards, patient identification discrepancies must be resolved before specimen collection proceeds. This is particularly important for blood bank samples like group and screen, where misidentification could lead to incompatible blood transfusions with potentially fatal consequences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed with collection as the difference is minor\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate and potentially dangerous. Even minor discrepancies in patient identification can lead to serious errors. The difference between \u0022Wilson\u0022 and \u0022Wilton\u0022 may seem minor, but it could potentially result in the specimen being attributed to the wrong patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollect the specimen but mark it as potentially mislabelled\u003C/strong\u003E does not resolve the identification issue and may create confusion in the laboratory. Specimens with unresolved identification issues should not be collected until the discrepancy is resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsk the patient to confirm her identity verbally and proceed\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient. While verbal confirmation is part of the identification process, it does not override the need for matching written documentation. Patients may be confused or misunderstand, particularly when unwell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse only the medical record number for identification\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as proper patient identification requires at least three identifiers. Relying on a single identifier, even if it\u0027s the medical record number, does not meet safety standards for specimen collection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Specimen collection should be delayed when there is a patient identification discrepancy until the discrepancy is resolved.","Patient request forms require three approved identifiers including full name, date of birth, and medical record number.","Correct patient identification is essential to prevent specimen misidentification errors that can lead to patient harm."],"references":["National Pathology Accreditation Advisory Council. Requirements for Medical Pathology Services. 3rd ed. Canberra: Australian Government Department of Health; 2018. Available from: https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/publications-and-resources/resource-library/requirements-medical-pathology-services-third-edition-2018"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79426"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79426"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:36:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:38:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13599"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96811"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"